{
  "doc_id": "39725",
  "text": "As well as likelihood of escape, proximity to a place of safety can also influence whether animals choose to adopt a strategy of TI or attempt to flee from a predator. [CITATION_1] demonstrated in a laboratory that rabbits (Oryctolagus cuniculus) decreased the duration of TI as proximity to a human decreased or as proximity to their home cage increased. Likewise, [CITATION_2] found that TI was of shorter duration in Carolina anole lizards (Anolis carolinensis) that had been immobilised near large bushes than those immobilised in the absence of nearby protective cover. Further, O'Brien and [CITATION_3] reported that blue crabs (Callinectes sapidus) immobilised on a sandy substrate (in which they could seek cover by burying themselves) exhibited shorter durations of TI than individuals similarly immobilised on a hard surface (on which burying themselves for protection was not possible).",
  "correct_citation": {
